comment_data.body: AI (@pq): investigate.  This may be a limitation of how we're dealing with what we're seeing from the parser.

Confirmed no completions.

![screen shot 2017-05-10 at 12 08 45 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/67586/25916445/7c900ff6-3579-11e7-9013-bccffbc0a55f.png)

even w/ `new` cue:

![screen shot 2017-05-10 at 12 08 57 pm](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/67586/25916446/7c91dd22-3579-11e7-8aa2-3b1bb2b7c952.png)


@danrubel : maybe we can look together at the AST and see what case we need to provision for?

This is super annoying, and something you hit whenever you edit the first element in a list of widgets. @pq any news?

@devoncarew I'd like to nominate this for M21.
Btw, this works in vsCode, so I assume this is somehow an IJ issue?

> Btw, this works in vsCode, so I assume this is somehow an IJ issue?

This is surprising.  I'd expect the behavior to be the same unless we don't send requests from IntelliJ in some cases?

cc @danrubel @alexander-doroshko

Here are a couple of illustrations. Looks like maybe code completions don't work in IJ when the separating comma is missing?

*vsCode*:

![ij2](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13644170/34568882-7c8f488c-f167-11e7-8c28-77bf6bcdbaf4.gif)

*IntelliJ*:

![ij3](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/13644170/34568962-a88756c8-f167-11e7-8d3c-155310b1c2cb.gif)

This is a bug in the Dart plugin, it filters out all the received completion variants for this case. It should be easy to fix, thanks for letting me know! I'll fix it as soon as I'm back in the office next week.

@alexander-doroshko It would be great to know when the Dart plugin changes or filters out code completion suggestions. Those situations probably indicate areas where the analysis server code completion returns (or used to return) poor results. Could you provide us a list of when code completion suggestions are filtered out? Or point us to the code where this filtering occurs?

@danrubel It's filtering by prefix. 
If `foo` is typed before the caret then `fooBar` matches, `FooBar` doesn't match if case-sensitive first letter check is enabled, `bazFoo` matches if middle-matching is enabed, but `qwerty` is always filtered out.
The problem with this example is that prefix is calculated incorrectly. There should be no prefix at all, but IDE thinks it is `<Widget>[ new` and filters out everything.
I don't think you may use this knowledge to test analysis server :).
Fixed in 2018.1 branch. EAPs will start soon.

Confirmed this works w/ the latest Dart Plugin in 2017.3+.
